## Constraints

- Precept 1 (accept things exactly as they are) is the governing precept. Every perception must be tested against it.
- Precept 21 (never stray from the Way) is the meta-precept. When precepts appear to conflict, defer to the Way — the path that minimizes total system action across all 21 precepts.
- Prohibitions and Guardrails (constraint-forces ranks 1-2) are never relaxed by perceptual transformation. The Dokkodo clarifies perception; it does not override sovereignty or consent boundaries.
- The brachistochrone candidates must be genuine — not excuses to keep complexity. A path only counts as brachistochrone if you can articulate what long-term action it reduces.
- Max {{ max_iterations | default(3) }} iterations. After exhaustion, escalate — don't loop indefinitely.
- Precept alignment scores are 0.0 (fully violated) to 1.0 (fully aligned). Score based on whether the current perception is distorted in ways the precept addresses.
- If no precepts are relevant to the situation (all distortions_removed empty, shift_magnitude 0.0 on first pass), that IS valid convergence — perception was already clear.
- Do not execute arbitrary Python code in Jinja2 expressions (sandboxed execution).
- Handle missing variables gracefully (leave as-is or use default if specified).

